SIMPLE: prostration
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prostration
<hw>Pros*tra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>prostratio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>prostration</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of prostrating, throwing down, or laying fiat; <as>as, the
<ex>prostration</ex> of the body</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of falling down, or of bowing in humility or
adoration; primarily, the act of falling on the face, but usually
applied to kneeling or bowing in reverence and worship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A greater <qex>prostration</qex> of reason than of body.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The condition of being prostrate; great depression;
lowness; dejection; <as>as, a <ex>postration</ex> of spirits</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧A sudden <xex>prostration</xex> of strength.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A latent, not an exhausted, state
of the vital energies; great oppression of natural strength and
vigor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Prostration</xex>, in its medical use, is analogous
to the state of a spring lying under such a weight that it is incapable
of action; while <xex>exhaustion</xex> is analogous to the state of a
spring deprived of its elastic powers. The word, however, is often used
to denote any great depression of the vital powers.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prostyle</ent>⟦br⟧
